         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>316</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>24</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... but he took on a second birth. From then, through the kalpas he enjoys the fruit of it ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>138</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the sacrifices of ... (worship?) such as illuminations not towards the sun [or] the fire ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2x"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">This <hi>kisāsal</hi> book should not be carried off to another parish of Porociṃ 8.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... diseases of the eyes (?) ... not even elephant's tusk <hi>gorocanā</hi> etc. ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they give a fruit, as much as the Buddha, the teacher, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>89</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... merit gives quickly [and] nicely great fruit. || In the <hi>kutsmāt</hi> [tune] || All sacrifices ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>404</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault2006c"/><citedRange>73-74</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... accumulated through many years, (this does not surpass the merit) of honouring the Buddha, the teacher, only once.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they come. 1. (||) The merit of honouring the Buddha, the teacher, (gives) divine (happiness) to the beings.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>75, 125</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he seizes the capacity to ..., (he obtains) superiority over all spirits [and] non-humans.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Vollkommenheit wird als das Übertreffen aller übermenschlichen Wesen verstanden.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Perfection is understood as surpassing all superhuman beings.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>241</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... it (scil. the merit) stops and destroys all evil actions (in) all (births) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the meritorious becomes without further ado certainly indeed (provided with) a beautiful (body?) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>100, 248</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>16</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>101</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... with the vehicle (of merit) he went to the <hi>nirvāṇa</hi>. Therefore, Sucitta, teach in the country of Gandhāra to the beings ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he who has merit (obtains) renown, or whose choice it is to seize the superior capacity.</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">According to Sieg/Siegling <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1921"/><citedRange>30</citedRange></bibl>, the ductus of this leaf is similar to the one of <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a1"/> - <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a53"/>, but its size and the line order speaks against this affilition. Note that the highest attested leaf number of the series <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a1"/> to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a53"/> is 121.</note><note corresp="#a2x" type="philcomment">Reading <hi>porociṃ āllakäṃ</hi> according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2014"/><citedRange>114</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment"><hi>ko eseñc</hi>: these akṣaras are to be deleted: the scribe started to write the following word <hi>kosne</hi> but erroneously repeated the preceding phrase.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment"><hi>ñä(kci suk)</hi>: cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a226"/> b7.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment"><hi>gorocanā</hi>: a kind of orpiment, i.e. arsenicum.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment"><hi>krä(ṃtsonāṃ)</hi>: tentative restoration with <hi>kräṃtso</hi> 'beautiful'. It may have been for instance <hi>kräṃtsonāṃ kapśiñño kaknu</hi> 'provided with a beautiful body' (cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a56"/> a3 <hi>kräntsonāṃ kapśi ///</hi>).</note><note corresp="#b5 #b6" type="philcomment">: the last part of line b5 and the whole of line b6 are metrical, the metre probably being 4 x 12 (5 + 7). This is supported by the syntax. The expected punctuation "(:)" can be restored after <hi>(pñ)i</hi> and before <hi>śpālunt</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
